<p>the department for business and trade estimates that unwanted subscriptions cost uk consumers £1.6 billion a year. that's gym memberships you stopped using, streaming services you forgot to cancel after the free trial, saas tools you bought for one project and kept paying for.</p>

<p>the subscription economy is built on inertia. companies know that signing up is easy and cancelling takes effort. the gap between those two things is revenue.</p>

<h4>the subscription trap</h4>

<p>auto-renewing subscriptions are convenient right up until they're not. the £9.99 streaming service. the £15 gym membership. the £49 annual software licence you bought for freelance work you did three years ago. individually, none of these will break your budget. collectively, they can easily reach £500–1,000 a year for the average household.</p>

<p>the cma has taken enforcement action against companies using "subscription traps" — contracts that auto-renew into long-term commitments with inadequate notice or confusing cancellation processes. but enforcement is reactive. by the time a company is investigated, thousands of consumers have already paid for services they didn't want.</p>

<h4>why a spreadsheet isn't the answer</h4>

<p>plenty of people try to track subscriptions in a spreadsheet. it works for about three months. then a new service starts, an old one changes its name, and the spreadsheet becomes stale. the maintenance overhead of a manual system is higher than the pain of overpaying — so the spreadsheet gets abandoned and the payments continue.</p>

<h4>what perch. does</h4>

<p>forward a receipt, invoice, or renewal notice. perch. identifies the provider, the amount, the frequency, and the renewal date. if it's a service you haven't forwarded again in six months, the verdict is likely cancel — with the cancellation deadline and any notice period clearly shown. no judgment. just the facts and a button to act on them.</p>
